# ONEVO C# Coding Standards

## Naming
- Classes: PascalCase (`EmployeeService`)
- Interfaces: IPascalCase (`IEmployeeRepository`)
- Methods: PascalCase + Async suffix (`GetByIdAsync()`)
- Private fields: _camelCase (`_repository`)
- DTOs: `{Entity}{Action}Dto` (e.g., `EmployeeListDto`)
- Commands: `{Action}{Entity}Command` (e.g., `CreateEmployeeCommand`)
- Optional events: `{Entity}{Action}Event` (e.g., `EmployeeTerminatedEvent`)

## Patterns
- Use `Result<T>` instead of throwing exceptions
- Use MediatR for command/query dispatch
- Use FluentValidation for request validation
- Put command validators beside their commands: `Commands/{UseCase}/{UseCase}Validator.cs`
- Use async/await with CancellationToken on ALL async methods
- Use BaseRepository<T> for data access (auto-filters by tenant)
- Use `[RequirePermission("resource:action")]` on all endpoints

## Module Boundaries
- Only import from other modules' `Public/` interfaces
- Never reference `*.Internal.*` from outside the module
- Use direct Application interfaces/services for normal cross-feature work
- Use domain events only for justified post-save side effects

## Database
- EF Core snake_case convention handles mapping
- UUID primary keys (Guid in C#)
- DateTimeOffset for timestamps, DateOnly for dates
- Encrypted fields via IEncryptionService (AES-256)

## Don't
- Don't use synchronous I/O
- Don't throw exceptions for business logic
- Don't bypass BaseRepository (loses tenant filtering)
- Don't use string for IDs (use Guid)
- Don't log PII (emails, names, phone numbers)
- Don't hardcode secrets
- Don't create `Events/`, `EventHandlers/`, or feature-level `Validators/` folders by default
